{% extends "layouts/base.njk" %}
{% import "partials/_demo.njk" as ui %}

{% block title %}Z-index · Stisla{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
  <header>
    <h1>Z-index</h1>
    <p class="lead">Shared stacking scale for floating components.</p>
  </header>

  <section>
    <p>Floating and overlay components compete for the same paint order. Stisla pins each family to a fixed <code>z-index</code> band so dialogs sit above drawers, tooltips sit above their triggers, and toasts win over everything. Stay inside the band when you build custom overlays and the stack stays predictable.</p>
    <p>Values start at <code>1030</code> and step by tens. The gaps leave room for project-specific layers like a fixed page header, a banner, or a debug panel, without forcing every component above to shift.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>The scale</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Component</th>
          <th>Variable</th>
          <th>Value</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><a href="/menu">Dropdown</a></td><td><code>--menu-z-index</code></td><td>1030</td></tr>
        <tr><td><a href="/app-shell">App-shell sidebar</a></td><td><code>--app-shell-sidebar-z</code></td><td>1030</td></tr>
        <tr><td><a href="/drawer">Drawer</a></td><td><code>--drawer-z-index</code></td><td>1045</td></tr>
        <tr><td><a href="/tooltip">Tooltip</a></td><td><code>--tooltip-z-index</code></td><td>1050</td></tr>
        <tr><td><a href="/dialog">Dialog</a></td><td><code>--dialog-z-index</code></td><td>1055</td></tr>
        <tr><td><a href="/popover">Popover</a></td><td><code>--popover-z-index</code></td><td>1070</td></tr>
        <tr><td><a href="/toast">Toast</a></td><td><code>--toast-z-index</code></td><td>1090</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p>Sidebar and dropdown share <code>1030</code> on purpose. They never co-exist in the same stacking context (the sidebar is fixed layout chrome, a dropdown opens inside content).</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Overriding per instance</h2>
    <p>Every overlay reads its <code>z-index</code> from a CSS variable. Set the variable on the component (or any ancestor) to lift one instance without touching the global scale.</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='html') %}
    <div class="menu" style="--menu-z-index: 1500;">
      <!-- this dropdown floats above everything else -->
    </div>
    {% endcall %}
    <p>Prefer this over a one-off <code>!important</code>. The variable name is component-scoped so the override doesn&rsquo;t leak.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Working alongside the scale</h2>
    <p>Custom overlays land cleanly when they pick a value with room around them.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Page chrome that should sit under every Stisla overlay (a sticky header, a banner, a sidebar handle) goes below the scale, in the <code>1</code>&ndash;<code>1020</code> range.</li>
      <li>One-off layers that need to slot between two component families fit at <code>1035</code>, <code>1060</code>, or <code>1080</code>. A custom backdrop between drawer and tooltip lives at <code>1047</code>, a search palette between dialog and popover at <code>1060</code>.</li>
      <li>Debug overlays, dev tooling, and accessibility shims that must win against every shipped component sit above the scale at <code>1100</code> or higher.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Inside a single component, low single-digit values (<code>1</code>, <code>2</code>, <code>3</code>) handle local stacking like overlapping borders in a button group, a hover state that needs to win against a sibling, or an avatar that lifts above the rest of its group. These live in the component&rsquo;s own stacking context and don&rsquo;t interact with the table above.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Stacking contexts</h2>
    <p>Z-index only compares siblings inside the same stacking context. A component with a higher number can still render below a competitor if the competitor lives in a parent that already established a higher context. Two common ways to accidentally create a stacking context:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><code>position: relative</code> with any <code>z-index</code> other than <code>auto</code>.</li>
      <li><code>transform</code>, <code>filter</code>, <code>opacity</code> below <code>1</code>, <code>will-change</code>, or <code>isolation: isolate</code> on an ancestor.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>If a dropdown opens but renders below another element with a lower z-index, walk up the DOM and look for one of those properties on an ancestor. The fix is to move the overlay out of the broken context. Stisla&rsquo;s floating components use <code>@floating-ui/dom</code> with portal-style positioning by default to sidestep this exact class of bug.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>RTL</h2>
    <p>Stacking order is independent of writing direction. <code>dir="rtl"</code> flips inline axes but leaves the z-axis untouched. Every value in the table applies identically in LTR and RTL.</p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Customization</h2>
    <p>There is no shared Sass map for the scale. Each component declares its own <code>--{component}-z-index</code> default inside its own block selector (<code>.menu { --menu-z-index: 1030; &hellip; }</code>). One consequence: a <code>:root</code> override won&rsquo;t propagate. When the cascade reaches the component selector, the in-place declaration wins over the inherited <code>:root</code> value.</p>
    <p>For the common case of lifting one floating instance, use the inline-style hook shown in <a href="#overriding-per-instance">Overriding per instance</a>. To shift the whole scale at the project level, retarget each component selector and keep the spacing between families.</p>
    {% call ui.code(lang='css') %}
    .menu            { --menu-z-index:     2030; }
    .app-shell__sidebar  { --app-shell-sidebar-z:  2030; }
    .drawer              { --drawer-z-index:       2045; }
    .tooltip             { --tooltip-z-index:      2050; }
    .dialog              { --dialog-z-index:       2055; }
    .popover             { --popover-z-index:      2070; }
    .toast-region        { --toast-region-z-index: 2090; }
    .toast               { --toast-z-index:        2090; }
    {% endcall %}
    <p>Bumping every value by the same offset preserves the relative order. Reordering families is supported but risky. The defaults reflect the order users typically want (toasts above modals above tooltips), and changing them per component can produce surprising results when several overlays are open at once.</p>
  </section>
{% endblock %}
